probably that make-up was freely available to women. Before I came to Bahrain it was equivalent to Smiths coming to the UK in the early 90s and everywhere had Sunkist and McDonalds. However make-up available was generally all brands of the same colouring. I can safely say that Q8 that the tables have changed, colouring and choice for females is available but still not in a ratio where 50% is one colour and the other 50% another, it’s however clear the 50-50 is in the making.

Bahrain no no 1: Cheap booze

Cheep booze, this is relatively new here in Bahrain, the smokey night club on the Amwaj is there to cater of the drunken Brits guilty pleasures and most of us other nationalities are left watching the kids. This place has a bar and a dark room; we can only presume that the dark room is for Brits to go and relax in.

No 2. Googling in private

As I sat downstairs with my laptop on my knees one night my wife was ‘googling’ on her phone via the Wi-Fi. This was when it all went wrong! A mutual friend saw this share post and it was a baby shower in local format. YouTube soon appeared for more supporter and symbols.
